        <span class="eyebrow">Employer Branding</span>
        <h1>Employer Branding Video: Why It Matters to the People You Already Hired</h1>
        <p class="lead">Most companies commission an employer branding film with one job in mind: attract candidates. That's real, but it undersells the video — the same footage keeps working long after someone has already signed.</p>
        <p class="post-meta"><span>Viven Team</span> <span>·</span> <span>July 21, 2026</span></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="sec" style="padding-top:40px">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="post-wrap post-body reveal">
      <img src="https://www.viven.ch/projects/kpmg-consultepreneur-employer-branding/01-UNIVERSUM_KPMG_2.jpeg" alt="Employer Branding Video: Why It Matters to the People You Already Hired" loading="eager" style="width:100%;border-radius:16px;margin:8px 0 26px;aspect-ratio:16/9;object-fit:cover" />

      <h2>Recruiting isn't the only job it does</h2>
      <p>The people who watch an employer branding video aren't only outside candidates. Current employees see it too — in onboarding decks, at all-hands, shared in team channels — and it does something recruiting footage rarely gets credit for: it reminds the people already there why the place they chose still makes sense.</p>

      <h2>It's your best referral engine, if people actually want to share it</h2>
      <p>The cheapest, best-fit candidates rarely come from job ads — they come from referrals. People refer companies they're proud of, and a film that actually looks like the place they work, not a stock-footage version of it, is the kind employees will put on their own LinkedIn without being asked.</p>

      <h2>New hires decide whether to stay in the first weeks</h2>
      <p>A lot of early attrition happens because reality doesn't match what was promised at the interview. When the same honest culture that sold a candidate keeps showing up after they start — same faces, same spaces, same tone — there's no gap to be disappointed by. The film that got them through the door can keep doing work months after they accepted the offer.</p>

      <h2>Brands already doing this</h2>
      <p>Our employer branding work for UBS, Siemens and KPMG was built to attract specific candidate profiles — and in every case, the same film ended up circulating internally too, used in onboarding and shared by employees on their own. That double life is the point, not a bonus.</p>

      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/en/services/employer-branding/">employer branding</a> work, or <a href="/en/contact/">tell us what talent you want to attract and keep</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
